<br>
I don't see anyone arguing the fact that DAoC is still in Beta.  I am very very disappointed in the fact that we were lead to believe it was "finished".  Hell, your recommondation was one of the reasons I was looking forward to it.  But, as you can see, only being level 34 four months after launch, I don't worry about maximizing xp, I don't worry about equipment dropping.  I haven't read AT ALL about the DAoC quests other than one or two really hard spawns that I couldn't seem to find.  <br>
<br>
However, you seem to be going out of your way to show how many ways DAoC is just like EQ, but you don't like DAoC...:)<br>
<br>
You keep referring to this story that EQ has.  If you are referring to Giants hate Dwarves, mmmmm, ok.  But, for the most part, I frankly don't see it.  The best stories I ever got out of EQ were from my guild mates :)<br>
<br>
A Moon for Christ's sake?  /boggle<br>
<br>
<br>
<i><font color="blue">Contradiction. Increase RF. Than what? Everyone is running around with epics</font></i><br>
<br>
Right, just like Rogues, Druids and Monks...<br>
<br>
Why should my ability to get an item not be based upon my skill, rather than some absurb timer that Verant has put in to give items "rarity".  Damn, if I wanted to experience resource constraints of that magnitude, I would go pop in a tape of some old footage of the '73 oil embargo, or just wait till the next Texas summer when watering restrictions go into effect...<br>
<br>
<br>
<i><font color="blue">What did EQ do to copy UO?<br>
<br>
The answer is... ... ... ?</font></i><br>
<br>
<br>
EHHHHH.  The question is not what EQ did to copy UO, it's how did EQ position their game to compete with the unhappy UO players?  I am sure Verant had a VERY close look at all the aspects of UO, not just PvP.  Matter of fact, many UO players I speak to still can't come to grips with what DAoC and EQ are all about and how they are fun...<br>
<br>
<br>
<i><font color="blue">Now we will make you spend more time running around trying to find more things to kill at your level hoping to God you do not start taking base XP hits for camping penalties.</font></i><br>
<br>
I have NEVER had a problem finding things to kill, which I will say was NOT true of EQ.  EQ was busting at the seams before they EVER did a server split.<br>
<br>
<br>
<i><font color="blue">It will have no resale value because everyone can get them, and to top it off, lets make them degrade so we create a game with no economy! Woot.</font></i><br>
<br>
You hunt MOBS for resale value?  Shit, Ut.  I would of given you some of my equipment to sell.  I give the stuff I can't use to my friends.  I am actually damn proud that practically every piece of equipment my Cleric wore I "camped" myself, which is more the way the game should be played IMHO.<br>
<br>
Degrade?  Man, I wish items BROKE.  Make items break and up the drop rates about 1000%.  I love finding items.  I love the idea of that rare "GoblinSlayer" being in a pile of loot :)<br>
<br>
<br>
<i><font color="blue">We licensed our engine!</font></i><br>
<br>
I would do the same thing.  Its nuts to develop something for 10x the cost that won't be nearly as good.  I guess I better stop using IIS/Apache as my web server and write my own.  And I guess I had better start building my own fabrication plant so I can make my own chips, maybe buy a plot of land so I can raise my own chickens and cows......<br>
<br>
I think the graphics engine they licensed is very good.  There are a lot of games out there that are using it very successfully, and I would rather have Mythic (or any company I choose to support) not spending R&D bucks on products that have already been R&Ded by someone else...<br>
<br>
<br>
<i><font color="blue">And you get this in DAOC how? 1 hour of soloing a spawn that is always up and you want to get your 35th so called "Epic" before work?</font></i><br>
<br>
Frankly, I don't solo.  I abhor soloing.  If my friends aren't on or we haven't scheduled a play time, I simply don't play.  Too many other things to do on good 'ol Mother Earth than soloing in DAoC.<br>
<br>
<br>
<i><font color="blue">Back to the original quote - I would like to see someone create an MMORPG with an addicting economy like EQ has without rare and hard to get items. <br>
<br>
Please tell me where the challenge is in waking up with your level 25 character, a cup of coffee and a donut. Logging in to get the most prized epic at level 25 in 32 minutes which will become about as useful as a hooker in a catholic church with no resell ability.</font></i><br>
<br>
We are not arguing about challenge Ut.  I like a challenge.  Nothing like pulling 4 31+ MOBS when the average level in your group is 24.  Wheeeee.  That's some serious fun!<br>
<br>
DO you really think EQ is challenging?  Any lamoid can get to level 60 with enough time.  EQ is an exercise in patience.  How is ToV really ALL that different from KD or Guk King, I mean REALLY?<br>
<br>
I won't argue that DAoC suffers from the same thing of course.  It is very much like EQ, better in many ways, worse in others.  It's much easier to produce a hack-n-slash game than a game with real depth and story. <p>-----------<BR>
